# Cline Rules for E-Mobility Driver App

## Project Overview

This is a Vue.js-based e-mobility driver application with TypeScript, featuring charging station management, session tracking, badge management, and user authentication.

## Core Development Principles

### Keep It Simple

- Avoid over-engineering solutions
- Use built-in HTML form validation where possible
- Minimize external dependencies
- Focus on core functionality first
- Avoid complex state management patterns until necessary
- No premature optimization

### Code Quality Standards

- Follow TypeScript strict mode requirements
- Use ESLint and Prettier configurations consistently
- Maintain test coverage for critical functionality
- Write self-documenting code with clear naming
- Keep functions small and focused on single responsibilities

## Vue.js Specific Guidelines

### Component Structure

- Use Composition API for new components
- Keep components focused on single concerns
- Use `defineProps` and `defineEmits` with TypeScript
- Prefer `<script setup>` syntax for cleaner code
- Extract reusable logic into composables (`src/composables/`)

### State Management

- Use Pinia stores for global state (`src/store/`)
- Keep stores focused on specific domains (badges, sessions, users, etc.)
- Use composables for component-level reactive state
- Avoid prop drilling - use provide/inject when appropriate

### Styling

- Use scoped styles in components
- Follow existing CSS patterns and naming conventions
- Consider responsive design for mobile/desktop views
- Maintain consistency with UI5 design system

## TypeScript Guidelines

### Type Safety

- Define proper interfaces for all data structures
- Use the existing type definitions in `types/` directory
- Avoid `any` type - use proper typing or `unknown`
- Leverage union types and optional properties appropriately

### File Organization

- Keep type definitions in dedicated `.d.ts` files
- Export types from appropriate modules
- Use barrel exports for cleaner imports

## Testing Standards

### Unit Tests

- Write tests for all new components and composables
- Use Vitest/Jest with Vue Test Utils
- Focus on behavior testing over implementation details
- Mock external dependencies appropriately
- Maintain existing test patterns in `test/` directories

### Test Organization

- Mirror source directory structure in test directories
- Use descriptive test names that explain the scenario
- Group related tests using `describe` blocks
- Test both happy path and error scenarios

## API and Service Guidelines

### CDS Services

- Follow existing patterns in `srv/` directory
- Use proper error handling and validation
- Implement appropriate authorization checks
- Document service endpoints and data models

### External Services

- Use the existing external service patterns
- Implement proper token handling
- Add appropriate error handling and retries
- Cache responses when appropriate

### OData Integration

- Use existing OData utilities in `src/utils/odata/`
- Follow OData query patterns consistently
- Handle pagination and filtering properly

## File and Directory Structure

### Organization Principles

- Group related files by feature/domain
- Use consistent naming conventions
- Keep shared utilities in appropriate directories
- Separate concerns between components, pages, and services

### Import Guidelines

- Use relative imports for local files
- Use absolute imports for shared utilities
- Group imports: external libraries, internal modules, types
- Remove unused imports

## Security Considerations

### Authentication

- Use existing XSUAA integration patterns
- Implement proper session management
- Follow SAP BTP security guidelines
- Validate user permissions appropriately

### Data Handling

- Sanitize user inputs
- Use proper error messages that don't leak sensitive information
- Follow GDPR/privacy requirements for user data

## Performance Guidelines

### Bundle Optimization

- Use dynamic imports for route-based code splitting
- Optimize images and assets
- Minimize bundle size with tree shaking
- Use Vite build optimizations

### Runtime Performance

- Implement virtual scrolling for large lists
- Use proper caching strategies
- Avoid memory leaks in components
- Profile performance in development

## Deployment and DevOps

### Build Process

- Use existing MTA build configuration
- Follow SAP BTP deployment patterns
- Maintain environment-specific configurations
- Use proper versioning and changelog management

### Configuration Management

- Use environment variables for different stages
- Keep sensitive data in proper credential stores
- Document configuration requirements

## Code Review Guidelines

### Before Submitting

- Run tests and ensure they pass
- Check linting and formatting
- Verify TypeScript compilation
- Test functionality in browser
- Update documentation if needed

### Review Checklist

- Code follows established patterns
- Tests are adequate and passing
- Performance implications considered
- Security aspects reviewed
- Documentation is updated

## Domain-Specific Guidelines

### E-Mobility Features

- Understand charging station status workflows
- Implement proper session state management
- Handle badge authentication flows correctly
- Consider real-time updates for station availability
- Implement proper error handling for charging operations

### User Experience

- Provide clear feedback for charging operations
- Handle offline scenarios gracefully
- Implement proper loading states
- Ensure accessibility compliance
- Test on mobile devices

## Documentation Requirements

### Code Documentation

- Document complex business logic
- Explain non-obvious technical decisions
- Keep README files updated
- Document API changes and breaking changes

### User Documentation

- Maintain user guides for new features
- Document configuration and setup procedures
- Keep troubleshooting guides current

## Error Handling

### Frontend Errors

- Implement global error handling
- Provide user-friendly error messages
- Log errors appropriately for debugging
- Handle network failures gracefully

### Service Errors

- Use proper HTTP status codes
- Implement structured error responses
- Log errors with sufficient context
- Handle business logic errors appropriately

## Migration and Updates

### Dependencies

- Keep dependencies updated regularly
- Test thoroughly after major updates
- Document breaking changes
- Maintain backward compatibility when possible

### Framework Updates

- Follow Vue.js migration guides
- Update TypeScript and tooling consistently
- Test all functionality after framework updates
